sec-object.hasown.name: hasOwn
sec-object.hasown.summary: The Object.hasOwn() static method returns true if the specified object has the indicated property as its own property. If the property is inherited, or does not exist, the method returns false.
sec-object.hasown.title: Object.hasOwn()

sec-object.prototype.hasownproperty.name: hasOwnProperty
sec-object.prototype.hasownproperty.summary: The hasOwnProperty() method returns a boolean indicating whether the object has the specified property as its own property (as opposed to inheriting it).
sec-object.prototype.hasownproperty.title: Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty()

sec-object.is.name: is
sec-object.is.summary: The Object.is() method determines whether two values are the same value.
sec-object.is.title: Object.is()

sec-object.isextensible.name: isExtensible
sec-object.isextensible.summary: The Object.isExtensible() method determines if an object is extensible (whether it can have new properties added to it).
sec-object.isextensible.title: Object.isExtensible()

sec-object.isfrozen.name: isFrozen
sec-object.isfrozen.summary: The Object.isFrozen() determines if an object is frozen.
sec-object.isfrozen.title: Object.isFrozen()

sec-object.prototype.isprototypeof.name: isPrototypeOf
sec-object.prototype.isprototypeof.summary: The isPrototypeOf() method checks if an object exists in another object's prototype chain.
sec-object.prototype.isprototypeof.title: Object.prototype.isPrototypeOf()

sec-object.issealed.name: isSealed
sec-object.issealed.summary: The Object.isSealed() method determines if an object is sealed.
sec-object.issealed.title: Object.isSealed()

sec-object.keys.name: keys
sec-object.keys.summary: The Object.keys() method returns an array of a given object's own enumerable property names, iterated in the same order that a normal loop would.
sec-object.keys.title: Object.keys()

sec-object.preventextensions.name: preventExtensions
sec-object.preventextensions.summary: The Object.preventExtensions() method prevents new properties from ever being added to an object (i.e. prevents future extensions to the object). It also prevents the object's prototype from being re-assigned.
sec-object.preventextensions.title: Object.preventExtensions()

sec-object.prototype.propertyisenumerabl.name: propertyIsEnumerable
sec-object.prototype.propertyisenumerabl.summary: The propertyIsEnumerable() method returns a boolean indicating whether the specified property is the object's enumerable own property.
sec-object.prototype.propertyisenumerabl.title: Object.prototype.propertyIsEnumerable()

sec-object.seal.name: seal
sec-object.seal.summary: The Object.seal() method seals an object. Sealing an object prevents extensions and makes existing properties non-configurable. A sealed object has a fixed set of properties: new properties cannot be added, existing properties cannot be removed, their enumerability and configurability cannot be changed, and its prototype cannot be re-assigned. Values of existing properties can still be changed as long as they are writable. seal() returns the same object that was passed in.
sec-object.seal.title: Object.seal()

sec-object.setprototypeof.name: setPrototypeOf
sec-object.setprototypeof.summary: The Object.setPrototypeOf() method sets the prototype (i.e., the internal [[Prototype]] property) of a specified object to another object or null.
sec-object.setprototypeof.title: Object.setPrototypeOf()

sec-object.prototype.tolocalestring.name: toLocaleString
sec-object.prototype.tolocalestring.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the object. This method is meant to be overridden by derived objects for locale-specific purposes.
sec-object.prototype.tolocalestring.title: Object.prototype.toLocaleString()

sec-object.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-object.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the object. This method is meant to be overridden by derived objects for custom type conversion logic.
sec-object.prototype.tostring.title: Object.prototype.toString()

sec-object.prototype.valueof.name: valueOf
sec-object.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method of Object converts the this value to an object. This method is meant to be overridden by derived objects for custom type conversion logic.
sec-object.prototype.valueof.title: Object.prototype.valueOf()

sec-object.values.name: values
sec-object.values.summary: The Object.values() method returns an array of a given object's own enumerable property values, in the same order as that provided by a for...in loop. (The only difference is that a for...in loop enumerates properties in the prototype chain as well.)
sec-object.values.title: Object.values()

sec-object-objects.name: Object
sec-object-objects.summary: The Object type represents one of JavaScript's data types. It is used to store various keyed collections and more complex entities. Objects can be created using the Object() constructor or the object initializer / literal syntax.
sec-object-objects.title: Object

sec-promise-constructor.name: Promise
sec-promise-constructor.summary: The Promise constructor is primarily used to wrap functions that do not already support promises.

firefox.notes: Constructor requires a new operator since version 37.

nodejs.notes: Constructor requires a new operator since version 4.

safari.notes: Constructor requires a new operator since version 10.

sec-promise-constructor.title: Promise() constructor

sec-promise.all.name: all
sec-promise.all.summary: The Promise.all() method takes an iterable of promises as input and returns a single Promise. This returned promise fulfills when all of the input's promises fulfill (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an array of the fulfillment values. It rejects when any of the input's promises rejects, with this first rejection reason.
sec-promise.all.title: Promise.all()

sec-promise.allsettled.name: allSettled
sec-promise.allsettled.summary: The Promise.allSettled() method takes an iterable of promises as input and returns a single Promise. This returned promise fulfills when all of the input's promises settle (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an array of objects that describe the outcome of each promise.
sec-promise.allsettled.title: Promise.allSettled()

sec-promise.any.name: any
sec-promise.any.summary: The Promise.any() method takes an iterable of promises as input and returns a single Promise. This returned promise fulfills when any of the input's promises fulfills, with this first fulfillment value. It rejects when all of the input's promises reject (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an AggregateError containing an array of rejection reasons.
sec-promise.any.title: Promise.any()

sec-promise.prototype.catch.name: catch
sec-promise.prototype.catch.summary: The catch() method returns a Promise and deals with rejected cases only. It behaves the same as calling Promise.prototype.then(undefined, onRejected) (in fact, calling obj.catch(onRejected) internally calls obj.then(undefined, onRejected)). This means that you have to provide an onRejected function even if you want to fall back to an undefined result value - for example obj.catch(() => {}).
sec-promise.prototype.catch.title: Promise.prototype.catch()

sec-promise.prototype.finally.name: finally
sec-promise.prototype.finally.summary: The finally() method of a Promise schedules a function, the callback function, to be called when the promise is settled. Like then() and catch(), it immediately returns an equivalent Promise object, allowing you to chain calls to another promise method, an operation called composition.
sec-promise.prototype.finally.title: Promise.prototype.finally()

sec-promise.race.name: race
sec-promise.race.summary: The Promise.race() method takes an iterable of promises as input and returns a single Promise. This returned promise settles with the eventual state of the first promise that settles.
sec-promise.race.title: Promise.race()

sec-promise.reject.name: reject
sec-promise.reject.summary: The Promise.reject() method returns a Promise object that is rejected with a given reason.
sec-promise.reject.title: Promise.reject()

sec-promise.resolve.name: resolve
sec-promise.resolve.summary: The Promise.resolve() method "resolves" a given value to a Promise. If the value is a promise, that promise is returned; if the value is a thenable, Promise.resolve() will call the then() method with two callbacks it prepared; otherwise the returned promise will be fulfilled with the value.
sec-promise.resolve.title: Promise.resolve()

sec-promise.prototype.then.name: then
sec-promise.prototype.then.summary: The then() method returns a Promise. It takes up to two arguments: callback functions for the success and failure cases of the Promise.
sec-promise.prototype.then.title: Promise.prototype.then()

sec-promise-objects.name: Promise
sec-promise-objects.summary: The Promise object represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value.
sec-promise-objects.title: Promise

sec-proxy-constructor.name: Proxy
sec-proxy-constructor.summary: The Proxy() constructor is used to create Proxy objects.
sec-proxy-constructor.title: Proxy() constructor

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: apply
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.apply() method is a trap for a function call.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.apply()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: construct
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.construct() method is a trap for the new operator. In order for the new operation to be valid on the resulting Proxy object, the target used to initialize the proxy must itself have a [[Construct]] internal method (i.e. new target must be valid).
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.construct()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: defineProperty
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.defineProperty() method is a trap for Object.defineProperty().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.defineProperty()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: deleteProperty
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.deleteProperty() method is a trap for the delete operator.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.deleteProperty()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: get
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.get() method is a trap for getting a property value.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.get()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: getOwnPropertyDescriptor
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.getOwnPropertyDescriptor() method is a trap for Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.getOwnPropertyDescriptor()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: getPrototypeOf
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.getPrototypeOf() method is a trap for the [[GetPrototypeOf]] internal method.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.getPrototypeOf()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: has
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.has() method is a trap for the in operator.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.has()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: isExtensible
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.isExtensible() method is a trap for Object.isExtensible().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.isExtensible()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: ownKeys
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.ownKeys() method is a trap for Reflect.ownKeys().

firefox.notes: In Firefox 42, the implementation got updated to reflect the final ES2015 specification: The result is now checked if it is an array and if the array elements are either of type string or of type symbol. Enumerating duplicate own property names is not a failure anymore.

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.ownKeys()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: preventExtensions
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.preventExtensions() method is a trap for Object.preventExtensions().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.preventExtensions()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: set
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.set() method is a trap for setting a property value.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.set()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: setPrototypeOf
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.setPrototypeOf() method is a trap for Object.setPrototypeOf().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.setPrototypeOf()

sec-proxy.revocable.name: revocable
sec-proxy.revocable.summary: The Proxy.revocable() static method creates a revocable Proxy object.
sec-proxy.revocable.title: Proxy.revocable()

sec-proxy-objects.name: Proxy
sec-proxy-objects.summary: The Proxy object enables you to create a proxy for another object, which can intercept and redefine fundamental operations for that object.
sec-proxy-objects.title: Proxy

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: RangeError
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.summary: The RangeError object indicates an error when a value is not in the set or range of allowed values.
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.title: RangeError

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: ReferenceError
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.summary: The ReferenceError object represents an error when a variable that doesn't exist (or hasn't yet been initialized) in the current scope is referenced.
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.title: ReferenceError

sec-reflect.apply.name: apply
sec-reflect.apply.summary: The static Reflect.apply() method calls a target function with arguments as specified.
sec-reflect.apply.title: Reflect.apply()

sec-reflect.construct.name: construct
sec-reflect.construct.summary: The static Reflect.construct() method acts like the new operator, but as a function. It is equivalent to calling new target(...args). It gives also the added option to specify a different prototype.
sec-reflect.construct.title: Reflect.construct()

sec-reflect.defineproperty.name: defineProperty
sec-reflect.defineproperty.summary: The static Reflect.defineProperty() method is like Object.defineProperty() but returns a Boolean.
sec-reflect.defineproperty.title: Reflect.defineProperty()

sec-reflect.deleteproperty.name: deleteProperty
sec-reflect.deleteproperty.summary: The static Reflect.deleteProperty() method allows to delete properties. It is like the delete operator as a function.
sec-reflect.deleteproperty.title: Reflect.deleteProperty()

sec-reflect.get.name: get
sec-reflect.get.summary: The static Reflect.get() method works like getting a property from an object (target[propertyKey]) as a function.
sec-reflect.get.title: Reflect.get()

sec-reflect.getownpropertydescriptor.name: getOwnPropertyDescriptor
sec-reflect.getownpropertydescriptor.summary: The static Reflect.getOwnPropertyDescriptor() method is similar to Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(). It returns a property descriptor of the given property if it exists on the object, undefined otherwise.
sec-reflect.getownpropertydescriptor.title: Reflect.getOwnPropertyDescriptor()

sec-reflect.getprototypeof.name: getPrototypeOf
sec-reflect.getprototypeof.summary: The static Reflect.getPrototypeOf() method is almost the same method as Object.getPrototypeOf(). It returns the prototype (i.e. the value of the internal [[Prototype]] property) of the specified object.
sec-reflect.getprototypeof.title: Reflect.getPrototypeOf()

sec-reflect.has.name: has
sec-reflect.has.summary: The static Reflect.has() method works like the in operator as a function.
sec-reflect.has.title: Reflect.has()

sec-reflect.isextensible.name: isExtensible
sec-reflect.isextensible.summary: The static Reflect.isExtensible() method determines if an object is extensible (whether it can have new properties added to it). It is similar to Object.isExtensible(), but with some differences.
sec-reflect.isextensible.title: Reflect.isExtensible()

sec-reflect.ownkeys.name: ownKeys
sec-reflect.ownkeys.summary: The static Reflect.ownKeys() method returns an array of the target object's own property keys.
sec-reflect.ownkeys.title: Reflect.ownKeys()

sec-reflect.preventextensions.name: preventExtensions
sec-reflect.preventextensions.summary: The static Reflect.preventExtensions() method prevents new properties from ever being added to an object (i.e., prevents future extensions to the object). It is similar to Object.preventExtensions(), but with some differences.
sec-reflect.preventextensions.title: Reflect.preventExtensions()

sec-reflect.set.name: set
sec-reflect.set.summary: The static Reflect.set() method works like setting a property on an object.
sec-reflect.set.title: Reflect.set()

sec-reflect.setprototypeof.name: setPrototypeOf
sec-reflect.setprototypeof.summary: The static Reflect.setPrototypeOf() method is the same method as Object.setPrototypeOf(), except for its return type. It sets the prototype (i.e., the internal [[Prototype]] property) of a specified object to another object or to null, and returns true if the operation was successful, or false otherwise.
sec-reflect.setprototypeof.title: Reflect.setPrototypeOf()

sec-reflect-object.name: Reflect
sec-reflect-object.summary: Reflect is a built-in object that provides methods for interceptable JavaScript operations. The methods are the same as those of proxy handlers. Reflect is not a function object, so it's not constructible.
sec-reflect-object.title: Reflect

sec-regexp-constructor.name: RegExp
sec-regexp-constructor.summary: The RegExp constructor creates a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern.
sec-regexp-constructor.title: RegExp() constructor

sec-get-regexp.prototype.dotAll.name: dotAll
sec-get-regexp.prototype.dotAll.summary: The dotAll accessor property indicates whether or not the s flag is used with the regular expression.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.dotAll.title: RegExp.prototype.dotAll

sec-regexp.prototype.exec.name: exec
sec-regexp.prototype.exec.summary: The exec() method executes a search for a match in a specified string and returns a result array, or null.
sec-regexp.prototype.exec.title: RegExp.prototype.exec()

sec-get-regexp.prototype.flags.name: flags
sec-get-regexp.prototype.flags.summary: The flags accessor property represents the flags of the current regular expression object.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.flags.title: RegExp.prototype.flags

sec-get-regexp.prototype.global.name: global
sec-get-regexp.prototype.global.summary: The global accessor property indicates whether or not the g flag is used with the regular expression.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.global.title: RegExp.prototype.global

sec-get-regexp.prototype.hasIndices.name: hasIndices
sec-get-regexp.prototype.hasIndices.summary: The hasIndices accessor property indicates whether or not the d flag is used with the regular expression.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.hasIndices.title: RegExp.prototype.hasIndices

sec-get-regexp.prototype.ignorecase.name: ignoreCase
sec-get-regexp.prototype.ignorecase.summary: The ignoreCase accessor property indicates whether or not the i flag is used with the regular expression.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.ignorecase.title: RegExp.prototype.ignoreCase

sec-properties-of-regexp-instances.name: lastIndex
sec-properties-of-regexp-instances.summary: lastIndex is a read/write integer property of RegExp instances that specifies the index at which to start the next match.
sec-properties-of-regexp-instances.title: RegExp: lastIndex

sec-get-regexp.prototype.multiline.name: multiline
sec-get-regexp.prototype.multiline.summary: The multiline accessor property indicates whether or not the m flag is used with the regular expression.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.multiline.title: RegExp.prototype.multiline

sec-get-regexp.prototype.source.name: source
sec-get-regexp.prototype.source.summary: The source accessor property is a string containing the source text of the regex object, without the two forward slashes on both sides or any flags.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.source.title: RegExp.prototype.source

sec-get-regexp.prototype.sticky.name: sticky
sec-get-regexp.prototype.sticky.summary: The sticky accessor property indicates whether or not the y flag is used with the regular expression.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.sticky.title: RegExp.prototype.sticky

sec-regexp.prototype.test.name: test
sec-regexp.prototype.test.summary: The test() method executes a search for a match between a regular expression and a specified string. Returns true or false.
sec-regexp.prototype.test.title: RegExp.prototype.test()

sec-regexp.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-regexp.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the regular expression.
sec-regexp.prototype.tostring.title: RegExp.prototype.toString()

sec-get-regexp.prototype.unicode.name: unicode
sec-get-regexp.prototype.unicode.summary: The unicode accessor property indicates whether or not the u flag is used with the regular expression.

nodejs.notes: Case folding is implemented in version 8.6.0

sec-get-regexp.prototype.unicode.title: RegExp.prototype.unicode

sec-regexp.prototype-@@match.name: @@match
sec-regexp.prototype-@@match.summary: The [@@match]() method of a regular expression specifies how String.prototype.match() should behave. In addition, its presence (or absence) can influence whether an object is regarded as a regular expression.
sec-regexp.prototype-@@match.title: RegExp.prototype[@@match]()

sec-regexp-prototype-matchall.name: @@matchAll
sec-regexp-prototype-matchall.summary: The [@@matchAll]() method of a regular expression specifies how String.prototype.matchAll should behave.
sec-regexp-prototype-matchall.title: RegExp.prototype[@@matchAll]()

sec-regexp.prototype-@@replace.name: @@replace
sec-regexp.prototype-@@replace.summary: The [@@replace]() method of a regular expression specifies how String.prototype.replace() and String.prototype.replaceAll() should behave when the regular expression is passed in as the pattern.
sec-regexp.prototype-@@replace.title: RegExp.prototype[@@replace]()

sec-regexp.prototype-@@search.name: @@search
sec-regexp.prototype-@@search.summary: The [@@search]() method of a regular expression specifies how String.prototype.search should behave.
sec-regexp.prototype-@@search.title: RegExp.prototype[@@search]()

sec-get-regexp-@@species.name: @@species
sec-get-regexp-@@species.summary: The RegExp[@@species] accessor property returns the constructor used to construct copied regular expressions in certain RegExp methods.
sec-get-regexp-@@species.title: get RegExp[@@species]

sec-regexp.prototype-@@split.name: @@split
sec-regexp.prototype-@@split.summary: The [@@split]() method of a regular expression specifies how String.prototype.split should behave when the regular expression is passed in as the separator.
sec-regexp.prototype-@@split.title: RegExp.prototype[@@split]()

sec-regexp-regular-expression-objects.name: RegExp
sec-regexp-regular-expression-objects.summary: The RegExp object is used for matching text with a pattern.
sec-regexp-regular-expression-objects.title: RegExp

sec-set-constructor.name: Set
sec-set-constructor.summary: The Set constructor lets you create Set objects that store unique values of any type, whether primitive values or object references.
sec-set-constructor.title: Set() constructor

sec-set.prototype.add.name: add
sec-set.prototype.add.summary: The add() method inserts a new element with a specified value in to a Set object, if there isn't an element with the same value already in the Set.
sec-set.prototype.add.title: Set.prototype.add()

sec-set.prototype.clear.name: clear
sec-set.prototype.clear.summary: The clear() method removes all elements from a Set object.
sec-set.prototype.clear.title: Set.prototype.clear()

sec-set.prototype.delete.name: delete
sec-set.prototype.delete.summary: The delete() method removes a specified value from a Set object, if it is in the set.
sec-set.prototype.delete.title: Set.prototype.delete()

sec-set.prototype.entries.name: entries
sec-set.prototype.entries.summary: The entries() method returns a new Iterator object that contains an array of [value, value] for each element in the Set object, in insertion order. For Set objects there is no key like in Map objects. However, to keep the API similar to the Map object, each entry has the same value for its key and value here, so that an array [value, value] is returned.
sec-set.prototype.entries.title: Set.prototype.entries()

sec-set.prototype.foreach.name: forEach
sec-set.prototype.foreach.summary: The forEach() method executes a provided function once for each value in the Set object, in insertion order.
sec-set.prototype.foreach.title: Set.prototype.forEach()

sec-set.prototype.has.name: has
sec-set.prototype.has.summary: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an element with the specified value exists in a Set object or not.
sec-set.prototype.has.title: Set.prototype.has()

sec-get-set.prototype.size.name: size
sec-get-set.prototype.size.summary: The size accessor property returns the number of (unique) elements in a Set object.

firefox.notes: From Firefox 13 to Firefox 18, the size property was implemented as a Set.prototype.size() method, this has been changed to a property in later versions conform to the ECMAScript 2015 specification.

sec-get-set.prototype.size.title: Set.prototype.size

sec-set.prototype.values.name: values
sec-set.prototype.values.summary: The values() method returns a new Iterator object that contains the values for each element in the Set object in insertion order.
sec-set.prototype.values.title: Set.prototype.values()

sec-set.prototype-@@iterator.name: @@iterator
sec-set.prototype-@@iterator.summary: The @@iterator method of a Set object implements the iterable protocol and allows sets to be consumed by most syntaxes expecting iterables, such as the spread syntax and for...of loops. It returns an iterator that yields the values of the set.

firefox.notes: A placeholder property named @@iterator is used.
A placeholder property named iterator is used.

sec-set.prototype-@@iterator.title: Set.prototype[@@iterator]()

sec-get-set-@@species.name: @@species
sec-get-set-@@species.summary: The Set[@@species] accessor property is an unused accessor property specifying how to copy Set objects.
sec-get-set-@@species.title: get Set[@@species]

sec-set-objects.name: Set
sec-set-objects.summary: The Set object lets you store unique values of any type, whether primitive values or object references.
sec-set-objects.title: Set

sec-sharedarraybuffer-constructor.name: SharedArrayBuffer
sec-sharedarraybuffer-constructor.summary: The SharedArrayBuffer() constructor is used to create a SharedArrayBuffer object representing a generic, fixed-length raw binary data buffer, similar to the ArrayBuffer object.
sec-sharedarraybuffer-constructor.title: SharedArrayBuffer() constructor

sec-get-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.byte.name: byteLength
sec-get-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.byte.summary: The byteLength accessor property represents the length of an SharedArrayBuffer in bytes.
sec-get-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.byte.title: SharedArrayBuffer.prototype.byteLength

sec-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.slice.summary: The SharedArrayBuffer.prototype.slice() method returns a new SharedArrayBuffer whose contents are a copy of this SharedArrayBuffer's bytes from begin, inclusive, up to end, exclusive. If either begin or end is negative, it refers to an index from the end of the array, as opposed to from the beginning. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.slice().
sec-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.slice.title: SharedArrayBuffer.prototype.slice()

sec-sharedarraybuffer-objects.name: SharedArrayBuffer
sec-sharedarraybuffer-objects.summary: The SharedArrayBuffer object is used to represent a generic, fixed-length raw binary data buffer, similar to the ArrayBuffer object, but in a way that they can be used to create views on shared memory. A SharedArrayBuffer is not a Transferable Object, unlike an ArrayBuffer which is transferable.
sec-sharedarraybuffer-objects.title: SharedArrayBuffer

sec-string-constructor.name: String
sec-string-constructor.summary: The String constructor is used to create a new String object. When called instead as a function, it performs type conversion to a primitive string, which is usually more useful.
sec-string-constructor.title: String() constructor

sec-string.prototype.at.name: at
sec-string.prototype.at.summary: The at() method takes an integer value and returns a new String consisting of the single UTF-16 code unit located at the specified offset. This method allows for positive and negative integers. Negative integers count back from the last string character.
sec-string.prototype.at.title: String.prototype.at()

sec-string.prototype.charat.name: charAt
sec-string.prototype.charat.summary: The String object's charAt() method returns a new string consisting of the single UTF-16 code unit located at the specified offset into the string.
sec-string.prototype.charat.title: String.prototype.charAt()

sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.name: charCodeAt
sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.summary: The charCodeAt() method returns an integer between 0 and 65535 representing the UTF-16 code unit at the given index.
sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.title: String.prototype.charCodeAt()

sec-string.prototype.codepointat.name: codePointAt
sec-string.prototype.codepointat.summary: The codePointAt() method returns a non-negative integer that is the Unicode code point value at the given position. Note that this function does not give the nth code point in a string, but the code point starting at the specified string index.
sec-string.prototype.codepointat.title: String.prototype.codePointAt()

sec-string.prototype.concat.name: concat
sec-string.prototype.concat.summary: The concat() method concatenates the string arguments to the calling string and returns a new string.
sec-string.prototype.concat.title: String.prototype.concat()

sec-string.prototype.endswith.name: endsWith
sec-string.prototype.endswith.summary: The endsWith() method determines whether a string ends with the characters of a specified string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.endswith.title: String.prototype.endsWith()

sec-string.fromcharcode.name: fromCharCode
sec-string.fromcharcode.summary: The static String.fromCharCode() method returns a string created from the specified sequence of UTF-16 code units.
sec-string.fromcharcode.title: String.fromCharCode()

sec-string.fromcodepoint.name: fromCodePoint
sec-string.fromcodepoint.summary: The static String.fromCodePoint() method returns a string created by using the specified sequence of code points.
sec-string.fromcodepoint.title: String.fromCodePoint()

sec-string.prototype.includes.name: includes
sec-string.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method performs a case-sensitive search to determine whether one string may be found within another string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.includes.title: String.prototype.includes()

sec-string.prototype.indexof.name: indexOf
sec-string.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method, given one argument: a substring to search for, searches the entire calling string, and returns the index of the first occurrence of the specified substring. Given a second argument: a number, the method returns the first occurrence of the specified substring at an index greater than or equal to the specified number.
sec-string.prototype.indexof.title: String.prototype.indexOf()

sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.name: lastIndexOf
sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.summary: The lastIndexOf() method, given one argument: a substring to search for, searches the entire calling string, and returns the index of the last occurrence of the specified substring. Given a second argument: a number, the method returns the last occurrence of the specified substring at an index less than or equal to the specified number.
sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.title: String.prototype.lastIndexOf()

sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.name: length
sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.summary: The length read-only property of a string contains the length of the string in UTF-16 code units.
sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.title: String length

sec-string.prototype.localecompare.name: localeCompare
sec-string.prototype.localecompare.summary: The localeCompare() method returns a number indicating whether a reference string comes before, or after, or is the same as the given string in sort order. In implementations with Intl.Collator API support, this method simply calls Intl.Collator.
sec-string.prototype.localecompare.title: String.prototype.localeCompare()

sec-string.prototype.match.name: match
sec-string.prototype.match.summary: The match() method retrieves the result of matching a string against a regular expression.
sec-string.prototype.match.title: String.prototype.match()

sec-string.prototype.matchall.name: matchAll
sec-string.prototype.matchall.summary: The matchAll() method returns an iterator of all results matching a string against a regular expression, including capturing groups.
sec-string.prototype.matchall.title: String.prototype.matchAll()

sec-string.prototype.normalize.name: normalize
sec-string.prototype.normalize.summary: The normalize() method returns the Unicode Normalization Form of the string.
sec-string.prototype.normalize.title: String.prototype.normalize()

sec-string.prototype.padend.name: padEnd
sec-string.prototype.padend.summary: The padEnd() method pads the current string with a given string (repeated, if needed) so that the resulting string reaches a given length. The padding is applied from the end of the current string.
sec-string.prototype.padend.title: String.prototype.padEnd()

sec-string.prototype.padstart.name: padStart
sec-string.prototype.padstart.summary: The padStart() method pads the current string with another string (multiple times, if needed) until the resulting string reaches the given length. The padding is applied from the start of the current string.
sec-string.prototype.padstart.title: String.prototype.padStart()

sec-string.raw.name: raw
sec-string.raw.summary: The static String.raw() method is a tag function of template literals. This is similar to the r prefix in Python, or the @ prefix in C# for string literals. It's used to get the raw string form of template literals  that is, substitutions (e.g. ${foo}) are processed, but escape sequences (e.g. \n) are not.
sec-string.raw.title: String.raw()

sec-string.prototype.repeat.name: repeat
sec-string.prototype.repeat.summary: The repeat() method constructs and returns a new string which contains the specified number of copies of the string on which it was called, concatenated together.
sec-string.prototype.repeat.title: String.prototype.repeat()

sec-string.prototype.replace.name: replace
sec-string.prototype.replace.summary: The replace() method returns a new string with one, some, or all matches of a pattern replaced by a replacement. The pattern can be a string or a RegExp, and the replacement can be a string or a function called for each match. If pattern is a string, only the first occurrence will be replaced. The original string is left unchanged.

ie.notes: A replacement function as second argument is not supported.

sec-string.prototype.replace.title: String.prototype.replace()

sec-string.prototype.replaceall.name: replaceAll
sec-string.prototype.replaceall.summary: The replaceAll() method returns a new string with all matches of a pattern replaced by a replacement. The pattern can be a string or a RegExp, and the replacement can be a string or a function to be called for each match. The original string is left unchanged.
sec-string.prototype.replaceall.title: String.prototype.replaceAll()

sec-string.prototype.search.name: search
sec-string.prototype.search.summary: The search() method executes a search for a match between a regular expression and this String object.
sec-string.prototype.search.title: String.prototype.search()

sec-string.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-string.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method extracts a section of a string and returns it as a new string, without modifying the original string.
sec-string.prototype.slice.title: String.prototype.slice()

sec-string.prototype.split.name: split
sec-string.prototype.split.summary: The split() method takes a pattern and divides a String into an ordered list of substrings by searching for the pattern, puts these substrings into an array, and returns the array.
sec-string.prototype.split.title: String.prototype.split()

sec-string.prototype.startswith.name: startsWith
sec-string.prototype.startswith.summary: The startsWith() method determines whether a string begins with the characters of a specified string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.startswith.title: String.prototype.startsWith()

sec-string.prototype.substring.name: substring
sec-string.prototype.substring.summary: The substring() method returns the part of the string between the start and end indexes, or to the end of the string.
sec-string.prototype.substring.title: String.prototype.substring()

sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.name: toLocaleLowerCase
sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.summary: The toLocaleLowerCase() method returns the calling string value converted to lower case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.
sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.title: String.prototype.toLocaleLowerCase()

sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.name: toLocaleUpperCase
sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.summary: The toLocaleUpperCase() method returns the calling string value converted to upper case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.
sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.title: String.prototype.toLocaleUpperCase()

sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.name: toLowerCase
sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.summary: The toLowerCase() method returns the calling string value converted to lower case.
sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.title: String.prototype.toLowerCase()

sec-string.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-string.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified string value.
sec-string.prototype.tostring.title: String.prototype.toString()

sec-string.prototype.touppercase.name: toUpperCase
sec-string.prototype.touppercase.summary: The toUpperCase() method returns the calling string value converted to uppercase (the value will be converted to a string if it isn't one).
sec-string.prototype.touppercase.title: String.prototype.toUpperCase()

sec-string.prototype.trim.name: trim
sec-string.prototype.trim.summary: The trim() method removes whitespace from both ends of a string and returns a new string, without modifying the original string. Whitespace in this context is all the whitespace characters (space, tab, no-break space, etc.) and all the line terminator characters (LF, CR, etc.).
sec-string.prototype.trim.title: String.prototype.trim()

sec-string.prototype.trimend.name: trimEnd
sec-string.prototype.trimend.summary: The trimEnd() method removes whitespace from the end of a string. trimRight() is an alias of this method.
sec-string.prototype.trimend.title: String.prototype.trimEnd()

sec-string.prototype.trimstart.name: trimStart
sec-string.prototype.trimstart.summary: The trimStart() method removes whitespace from the beginning of a string. trimLeft() is an alias of this method.
sec-string.prototype.trimstart.title: String.prototype.trimStart()

sec-string.prototype.valueof.name: valueOf
sec-string.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of a String object.
sec-string.prototype.valueof.title: String.prototype.valueOf()

sec-string.prototype-@@iterator.name: @@iterator
sec-string.prototype-@@iterator.summary: The @@iterator method of a string implements the iterable protocol and allows strings to be consumed by most syntaxes expecting iterables, such as the spread syntax and for...of loops. It returns an iterator that yields the Unicode code points of the string value as individual strings.

firefox.notes: A placeholder property named @@iterator is used.
A placeholder property named iterator is used.

sec-string.prototype-@@iterator.title: String.prototype[@@iterator]()

sec-string-objects.name: String
sec-string-objects.summary: The String object is used to represent and manipulate a sequence of characters.
sec-string-objects.title: String

sec-symbol-constructor.name: Symbol
sec-symbol-constructor.summary: The Symbol() constructor returns a value of type symbol, but is incomplete as a constructor because it does not support the syntax "new Symbol()" and it is not intended to be subclassed. It may be used as the value of an extends clause of a class definition but a super call to it will cause an exception.
sec-symbol-constructor.title: Symbol() constructor

sec-symbol.asynciterator.name: asyncIterator
sec-symbol.asynciterator.summary: The Symbol.asyncIterator well-known symbol specifies the default async iterator for an object. If this property is set on an object, it is an async iterable and can be used in a for await...of loop.
sec-symbol.asynciterator.title: Symbol.asyncIterator

sec-symbol.prototype.description.name: description
sec-symbol.prototype.description.summary: The read-only description property is a string returning the optional description of Symbol objects.

safari.notes: No support for an undefined description.

sec-symbol.prototype.description.title: Symbol.prototype.description

sec-symbol.for.name: for
sec-symbol.for.summary: The Symbol.for(key) method searches for existing symbols in a runtime-wide symbol registry with the given key and returns it if found. Otherwise a new symbol gets created in the global symbol registry with this key.
sec-symbol.for.title: Symbol.for()

sec-symbol.hasinstance.name: hasInstance
sec-symbol.hasinstance.summary: The Symbol.hasInstance well-known symbol is used to determine if a constructor object recognizes an object as its instance. The instanceof operator's behavior can be customized by this symbol.
sec-symbol.hasinstance.title: Symbol.hasInstance

sec-symbol.isconcatspreadable.name: isConcatSpreadable
sec-symbol.isconcatspreadable.summary: The Symbol.isConcatSpreadable well-known symbol is used to configure if an object should be flattened to its array elements when using the Array.prototype.concat() method.
sec-symbol.isconcatspreadable.title: Symbol.isConcatSpreadable

sec-symbol.iterator.name: iterator
sec-symbol.iterator.summary: The well-known Symbol.iterator symbol specifies the default iterator for an object. Used by for...of.
sec-symbol.iterator.title: Symbol.iterator

sec-symbol.keyfor.name: keyFor
sec-symbol.keyfor.summary: The Symbol.keyFor(sym) method retrieves a shared symbol key from the global symbol registry for the given symbol.
sec-symbol.keyfor.title: Symbol.keyFor()

sec-symbol.match.name: match
sec-symbol.match.summary: The Symbol.match well-known symbol specifies the matching of a regular expression against a string. This function is called by the String.prototype.match() method.
sec-symbol.match.title: Symbol.match

sec-symbol.matchall.name: matchAll
sec-symbol.matchall.summary: The Symbol.matchAll well-known symbol specifies the method that returns an iterator, that yields matches of the regular expression against a string. This function is called by the String.prototype.matchAll() method.
sec-symbol.matchall.title: Symbol.matchAll

sec-symbol.replace.name: replace
sec-symbol.replace.summary: The Symbol.replace well-known symbol specifies the method that replaces matched substrings of a string. This function is called by the String.prototype.replace() method.
sec-symbol.replace.title: Symbol.replace

sec-symbol.search.name: search
sec-symbol.search.summary: The Symbol.search well-known symbol specifies the method that returns the index within a string that matches the regular expression. This function is called by the String.prototype.search() method.
sec-symbol.search.title: Symbol.search

sec-symbol.species.name: species
sec-symbol.species.summary: The well-known symbol Symbol.species specifies a function-valued property that the constructor function uses to create derived objects.
sec-symbol.species.title: Symbol.species

sec-symbol.split.name: split
sec-symbol.split.summary: The Symbol.split well-known symbol specifies the method that splits a string at the indices that match a regular expression. This function is called by the String.prototype.split() method.
sec-symbol.split.title: Symbol.split

sec-symbol.toprimitive.name: toPrimitive
sec-symbol.toprimitive.summary: The Symbol.toPrimitive well-known symbol specifies a method that accepts a preferred type and returns a primitive representation of an object. It is called in priority by all type coercion algorithms.
sec-symbol.toprimitive.title: Symbol.toPrimitive

sec-symbol.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-symbol.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified symbol value.
sec-symbol.prototype.tostring.title: Symbol.prototype.toString()

sec-symbol.tostringtag.name: toStringTag
sec-symbol.tostringtag.summary: The Symbol.toStringTag well-known symbol is a string valued property that is used in the creation of the default string description of an object. It is accessed internally by the Object.prototype.toString() method.
sec-symbol.tostringtag.title: Symbol.toStringTag

sec-symbol.unscopables.name: unscopables
sec-symbol.unscopables.summary: The Symbol.unscopables well-known symbol is used to specify an object value of whose own and inherited property names are excluded from the with environment bindings of the associated object.
sec-symbol.unscopables.title: Symbol.unscopables

sec-symbol.prototype.valueof.name: valueOf
sec-symbol.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of a Symbol object.
sec-symbol.prototype.valueof.title: Symbol.prototype.valueOf()

sec-symbol.prototype-@@toprimitive.name: @@toPrimitive
sec-symbol.prototype-@@toprimitive.summary: The [@@toPrimitive]() method converts a Symbol object to a primitive value.
sec-symbol.prototype-@@toprimitive.title: Symbol.prototype[@@toPrimitive]

sec-symbol-objects.name: Symbol
sec-symbol-objects.summary: Symbol is a built-in object whose constructor returns a symbol primitive  also called a Symbol value or just a Symbol  that's guaranteed to be unique. Symbols are often used to add unique property keys to an object that won't collide with keys any other code might add to the object, and which are hidden from any mechanisms other code will typically use to access the object. That enables a form of weak encapsulation, or a weak form of information hiding.
sec-symbol-objects.title: Symbol

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: SyntaxError
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.summary: The SyntaxError object represents an error when trying to interpret syntactically invalid code. It is thrown when the JavaScript engine encounters tokens or token order that does not conform to the syntax of the language when parsing code.
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.title: SyntaxError

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: TypeError
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.summary: The TypeError object represents an error when an operation could not be performed, typically (but not exclusively) when a value is not of the expected type.
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.title: TypeError

sec-typedarray.bytes_per_element.name: BYTES_PER_ELEMENT
sec-typedarray.bytes_per_element.summary: The TypedArray.BYTES_PER_ELEMENT property represents the size in bytes of each element in a typed array.
sec-typedarray.bytes_per_element.title: TypedArray.BYTES_PER_ELEMENT

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.at.name: at
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.at.summary: The at() method takes an integer value and returns the item at that index, allowing for positive and negative integers. Negative integers count back from the last item in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.at.title: TypedArray.prototype.at()

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.buffer.name: buffer
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.buffer.summary: The buffer accessor property represents the ArrayBuffer referenced by a TypedArray at construction time.
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.buffer.title: TypedArray.prototype.buffer

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.bytelengt.name: byteLength
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.bytelengt.summary: The byteLength accessor property represents the length (in bytes) of the typed array.
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.bytelengt.title: TypedArray.prototype.byteLength

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.byteoffse.name: byteOffset
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.byteoffse.summary: The byteOffset accessor property represents the offset (in bytes) of a typed array from the start of its ArrayBuffer.
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.byteoffse.title: TypedArray.prototype.byteOffset

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.copywithin.name: copyWithin
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.copywithin.summary: The copyWithin() method copies the sequence of array elements within the array to the position starting at target. The copy is taken from the index positions of the second and third arguments start and end. The end argument is optional and defaults to the length of the array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.copyWithin. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.copywithin.title: TypedArray.prototype.copyWithin()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.entries.name: entries
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.entries.summary: The entries() method returns a new Array iterator object that contains the key/value pairs for each index in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.entries.title: TypedArray.prototype.entries()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.every.name: every
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.every.summary: The every() method tests whether all elements in the typed array pass the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.every(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.every.title: TypedArray.prototype.every()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.fill.name: fill
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.fill.summary: The fill() method fills all the elements of a typed array from a start index to an end index with a static value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.fill(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.fill.title: TypedArray.prototype.fill()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.filter.name: filter
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.filter.summary: The filter() method creates a new typed array with all elements that pass the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.filter(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.filter.title: TypedArray.prototype.filter()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.find.name: find
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.find.summary: The find() method returns a value of an element in the typed array, if it satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise undefined is returned. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.find.title: TypedArray.prototype.find()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findindex.name: findIndex
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findindex.summary: The findIndex() method returns an index in the typed array, if an element in the typed array satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise -1 is returned.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findindex.title: TypedArray.prototype.findIndex()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlast.name: findLast
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlast.summary: The findLast() method iterates a typed array in reverse order and returns the value of the first element that satisfies the provided testing function. If no values satisfy the testing function, undefined is returned.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlast.title: TypedArray.prototype.findLast()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlastindex.name: findLastIndex
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlastindex.summary: The findLastIndex() method iterates a typed array in reverse order and returns the index of the first element that satisfies the provided testing function. If no values satisfy the testing function, -1 is returned.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlastindex.title: TypedArray.prototype.findLastIndex()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.foreach.name: forEach
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.foreach.summary: The forEach() method executes a provided function once per array element. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.forEach(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.foreach.title: TypedArray.prototype.forEach()

sec-%typedarray%.from.name: from
sec-%typedarray%.from.summary: The TypedArray.from() method creates a new typed array from an array-like or iterable object. This method is nearly the same as Array.from().
sec-%typedarray%.from.title: TypedArray.from()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.includes.name: includes
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method determines whether a typed array includes a certain element, returning true or false as appropriate. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.includes(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.includes.title: TypedArray.prototype.includes()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.indexof.name: indexOf
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method returns the first index at which a given element can be found in the typed array, or -1 if it is not present. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.indexOf(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 47, this method will no longer return -0. For example, new Uint8Array([0]).indexOf(0, -0) will now always return +0.

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.indexof.title: TypedArray.prototype.indexOf()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.join.name: join
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.join.summary: The join() method joins all elements of an array into a string. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.join(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.join.title: TypedArray.prototype.join()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.keys.name: keys
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.keys.summary: The keys() method returns a new array iterator object that contains the keys for each index in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.keys.title: TypedArray.prototype.keys()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.lastindexof.name: lastIndexOf
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.lastindexof.summary: The lastIndexOf() method returns the last index at which a given element can be found in the typed array, or -1 if it is not present. The typed array is searched backwards, starting at fromIndex. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.lastIndexOf(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 47, this method will no longer return -0. For example, new Uint8Array([0]).lastIndexOf(0, -0) will now always return +0.

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.lastindexof.title: TypedArray.prototype.lastIndexOf()

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.length.name: length
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.length.summary: The length accessor property represents the length (in elements) of a typed array.
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.length.title: TypedArray.prototype.length

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.name: map
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.summary: The map() method creates a new typed array with the results of calling a provided function on every element in this typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.map(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.title: TypedArray.prototype.map()

sec-properties-of-the-typedarray-constru.name: name
sec-properties-of-the-typedarray-constru.summary: The TypedArray.name property represents a string value of the typed array constructor name.
sec-properties-of-the-typedarray-constru.title: TypedArray.name

sec-%typedarray%.of.name: of
sec-%typedarray%.of.summary: The TypedArray.of() method creates a new typed array from a variable number of arguments. This method is nearly the same as Array.of().
sec-%typedarray%.of.title: TypedArray.of()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.name: reduce
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.summary: The reduce() method applies a function against an accumulator and each value of the typed array (from left-to-right) has to reduce it to a single value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reduce(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.title: TypedArray.prototype.reduce()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceright.name: reduceRight
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceright.summary: The reduceRight() method applies a function against an accumulator and each value of the typed array (from right-to-left) has to reduce it to a single value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reduceRight(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceright.title: TypedArray.prototype.reduceRight()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.name: reverse
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.summary: The reverse() method reverses a typed array in place. The first typed array element becomes the last and the last becomes the first. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reverse(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.title: TypedArray.prototype.reverse()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set.name: set
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set.summary: The set() method stores multiple values in the typed array, reading input values from a specified array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set.title: TypedArray.prototype.set()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method returns a new typed array (with a new underlying buffer), that contains a copy of a portion of the original typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.slice(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.title: TypedArray.prototype.slice()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.name: some
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.summary: The some() method tests whether some element in the typed array passes the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.some(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.title: TypedArray.prototype.some()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.sort.name: sort
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.sort.summary: The sort() method sorts the elements of a typed array numerically in place and returns the typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.sort(), except that sorts the values numerically instead of as strings. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.sort.title: TypedArray.prototype.sort()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.subarray.name: subarray
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.subarray.summary: The subarray() method returns a new TypedArray on the same ArrayBuffer store and with the same element types as for this TypedArray object. The begin offset is inclusive and the end offset is exclusive. TypedArray is one of the typed array types.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.subarray.title: TypedArray.prototype.subarray()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tolocalestrin.name: toLocaleString
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tolocalestrin.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the elements of the typed array. The elements are converted to strings and are separated by a locale-specific string (such as a comma ","). This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.toLocaleString() and, as the typed array elements are numbers, the same algorithm as Number.prototype.toLocaleString() applies for each element. sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: URIError

sec-weakmap-constructor.name: WeakMap
sec-weakmap-constructor.summary: The WeakMap() constructor creates a WeakMap object, optionally based on a provided Array or other iterable object.
sec-weakmap-constructor.title: WeakMap() constructor

sec-weakmap.prototype.delete.name: delete
sec-weakmap.prototype.delete.summary: The delete() method removes the specified element from a WeakMap object.

sec-weakmap.prototype.get.name: get
sec-weakmap.prototype.get.summary: The get() method returns a specified element from a WeakMap object.

sec-weakmap.prototype.has.name: has
sec-weakmap.prototype.has.summary: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an element with the specified key exists in the WeakMap object or not.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

sec-weakmap.prototype.has.title: WeakMap.prototype.has()

sec-weakmap.prototype.set.name: set
sec-weakmap.prototype.set.summary: The set() method adds a new element with a specified key and value to a WeakMap object.

sec-weakmap-objects.name: WeakMap
sec-weakmap-objects.summary: A WeakMap is a collection of key/value pairs whose keys must be objects, with values of any arbitrary JavaScript type, and which does not create strong references to its keys. sec-weakmap-objects.title: WeakMap

sec-weak-ref-constructor.name: WeakRef
sec-weak-ref-constructor.summary: The WeakRef constructor creates a WeakRef object referring to a given target object.

sec-weak-ref.prototype.deref.name: deref

sec-weak-ref.prototype.deref.title: WeakRef.prototype.deref()

sec-weak-ref-objects.name: WeakRef
sec-weak-ref-objects.summary: A WeakRef object lets you hold a weak reference to another object, without preventing that object from getting garbage-collected.
sec-weak-ref-objects.title: WeakRef

sec-weakset-constructor.name: WeakSet
sec-weakset-constructor.summary: The WeakSet constructor lets you create WeakSet objects that store weakly held objects in a collection.

sec-weakset.prototype.add.name: add

sec-weakset.prototype.delete.name: delete

sec-weakset.prototype.has.name: has

sec-weakset-objects.name: WeakSet
sec-weakset-objects.summary: The WeakSet object lets you store weakly held objects in a collection.

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: RuntimeError

sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.name: Infinity
sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.summary: The global property Infinity is a numeric value representing infinity.
sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.title: Infinity

sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.name: NaN
sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.summary: The global NaN property is a value representing Not-A-Number.
sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.title: NaN

sec-decodeuri-encodeduri.name: decodeURI
sec-decodeuri-encodeduri.summary: The decodeURI() function decodes a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) previously created by encodeURI() or by a similar routine.
sec-decodeuri-encodeduri.title: decodeURI()

sec-decodeuricomponent-encodeduricompone.name: decodeURIComponent
sec-decodeuricomponent-encodeduricompone.summary: The decodeURIComponent() function decodes a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) component previously created by encodeURIComponent or by a similar routine.
sec-decodeuricomponent-encodeduricompone.title: decodeURIComponent()

sec-encodeuri-uri.name: encodeURI
sec-encodeuri-uri.summary: The encodeURI() function encodes a URI by replacing each instance of certain characters by one, two, three, or four escape sequences representing the UTF-8 encoding of the character (will only be four escape sequences for characters composed of two "surrogate" characters).
sec-encodeuri-uri.title: encodeURI()

sec-encodeuricomponent-uricomponent.name: encodeURIComponent
sec-encodeuricomponent-uricomponent.summary: The encodeURIComponent() function encodes a URI by replacing each instance of certain characters by one, two, three, or four escape sequences representing the UTF-8 encoding of the character (will only be four escape sequences for characters composed of two "surrogate" characters).
sec-encodeuricomponent-uricomponent.title: encodeURIComponent()

sec-eval-x.name: eval
sec-eval-x.summary: The eval() function evaluates JavaScript code represented as a string and returns its completion value. The source is parsed as a script.
sec-eval-x.title: eval()

sec-globalthis.name: globalThis
sec-globalthis.summary: The global globalThis property contains the global this value, which is akin to the global object.
sec-globalthis.title: globalThis

sec-isfinite-number.name: isFinite
sec-isfinite-number.summary: The global isFinite() function determines whether the passed value is a finite number. If needed, the parameter is first converted to a number.
sec-isfinite-number.title: isFinite()

sec-isnan-number.name: isNaN
sec-isnan-number.summary: The isNaN() function determines whether a value is NaN or not. Because coercion inside the isNaN function can be surprising, you may alternatively want to use Number.isNaN().
sec-isnan-number.title: isNaN()

sec-parsefloat-string.name: parseFloat
sec-parsefloat-string.summary: The parseFloat() function parses a string argument and returns a floating point number.
sec-parsefloat-string.title: parseFloat()

sec-parseint-string-radix.name: parseInt
sec-parseint-string-radix.summary: The parseInt() function parses a string argument and returns an integer of the specified radix (the base in mathematical numeral systems).
sec-parseint-string-radix.title: parseInt()

sec-undefined.name: undefined
sec-undefined.summary: The global undefined property represents the primitive value undefined. It is one of JavaScript's primitive types.
sec-undefined.title: undefined

sec-static-semantics-constructormethod.name: constructor
sec-static-semantics-constructormethod.summary: The constructor method is a special method of a class for creating and initializing an object instance of that class.

sec-class-definitions.summary: The extends keyword is used in class declarations or class expressions to create a class that is a child of another class.
sec-class-definitions.title: extends

sec-class-definitions.name: static
sec-class-definitions.summary: The static keyword defines a static method or property for a class, or a class static initialization block (see the link for more information about this usage). Neither static methods nor static properties can be called on instances of the class. Instead, they're called on the class itself.
sec-class-definitions.title: static

sec-class-definitions.name: classes
sec-class-definitions.summary: Classes are a template for creating objects. They encapsulate data with code to work on that data. Classes in JS are built on prototypes but also have some syntax and semantics that are not shared with ES5 class-like semantics.
sec-class-definitions.title: Classes

sec-class-definitions.name: class
sec-class-definitions.summary: The class expression is one way to define a class. Similar to function expressions, class expressions can be named or unnamed. If named, the name of the class is local to the class body only.
sec-class-definitions.title: class expression

sec-class-definitions.name: class
sec-class-definitions.summary: The class declaration creates a new class with a given name using prototype-based inheritance.
sec-class-definitions.title: class

prod-ClassStaticBlock.title: Class static initialization blocks

sec-arguments-exotic-objects.name: callee
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.summary: The arguments.callee property contains the currently executing function.
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.title: arguments.callee

sec-arguments-exotic-objects.name: length
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.summary: The arguments.length property contains the number of arguments passed to the function.
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.title: arguments.length

sec-arguments-exotic-objects.name: arguments
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.summary: arguments is an Array-like object accessible inside functions that contains the values of the arguments passed to that function.
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.title: The arguments object

sec-arrow-function-definitions.name: arrow_functions
sec-arrow-function-definitions.summary: An arrow function expression is a compact alternative to a traditional function expression, but is limited and can't be used in all situations.

notes: The initial implementation of arrow functions in Firefox made them automatically strict. This has been changed as of Firefox 24. The use of 'use strict'; is now required.

sec-arrow-function-definitions.title: Arrow function expressions

sec-function-definitions.name: default_parameters
sec-function-definitions.summary: Default function parameters allow named parameters to be initialized with default values if no value or undefined is passed.
sec-function-definitions.title: Default parameters

sec-function-definitions.name: rest_parameters
sec-function-definitions.summary: The rest parameter syntax allows a function to accept an indefinite number of arguments as an array, providing a way to represent variadic functions in JavaScript.
sec-function-definitions.title: Rest parameters

sec-function-definitions.name: functions
sec-function-definitions.summary: Generally speaking, a function is a "subprogram" that can be called by code external (or internal in the case of recursion) to the function. sec-function-definitions.name: function
sec-function-definitions.summary: The function keyword can be used to define a function inside an expression.
sec-function-definitions.title: Function expression

sec-function-definitions.name: function
sec-function-definitions.summary: The function declaration (function statement) defines a function with the specified parameters.
sec-function-definitions.title: function declaration

sec-method-definitions.name: get
sec-method-definitions.summary: The get syntax binds an object property to a function that will be called when that property is looked up.
sec-method-definitions.title: getter

sec-method-definitions.name: method_definitions
sec-method-definitions.summary: Method definition is a shorter syntax for defining a function property in an object initializer.
sec-method-definitions.title: Method definitions

sec-method-definitions.name: set

sec-method-definitions.title: setter

sec-array-initializer.name: array_literals
sec-array-initializer.summary: This page describes JavaScript's lexical grammar. JavaScript source text is just a sequence of characters  in order for the interpreter to understand it, the string has to be parsed to a more structured representation. The initial step of parsing is called lexical analysis, in which the text gets scanned from left to right and is converted into a sequence of individual, atomic input elements. Some input elements are insignificant to the interpreter, and will be stripped after this step  they include control characters, line terminators, white space, and comments. The others, such as identifiers and punctuators, will be used for further syntax analysis. ECMAScript also defines certain keywords and literals and has rules for automatic insertion of semicolons to make certain invalid token sequences become valid.

If you want to add a new property, you can add a new line without modifying the previously last line if that line already uses a trailing comma. This makes version-control diffs cleaner and editing code might be less troublesome.
