sec-addition-operator-plus.name: addition
sec-addition-operator-plus.summary: The addition operator (+) produces the sum of numeric operands or string concatenation.
sec-addition-operator-plus.title: Addition (+)

sec-assignment-operators.name: addition_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The addition assignment operator (+=) adds the value of the right operand to a variable and assigns the result to the variable. The types of the two operands determine the behavior of the addition assignment operator. Addition or concatenation is possible.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Addition assignment (+=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The simple assignment operator (=) is used to assign a value to a variable. The assignment operation evaluates to the assigned value. Chaining the assignment operator is possible in order to assign a single value to multiple variables.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Assignment (=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: bitwise_and_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The bitwise AND assignment operator (&=) uses the binary representation of both operands, does a bitwise AND operation on them and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise AND assignment (&=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: bitwise_or_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The bitwise OR assignment operator (|=) uses the binary representation of both operands, does a bitwise OR operation on them and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise OR assignment (|=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: bitwise_xor_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The bitwise XOR assignment operator (^=) uses the binary representation of both operands, does a bitwise XOR operation on them and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise XOR assignment (^=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: division_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The division assignment operator (/=) divides a variable by the value of the right operand and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Division assignment (/=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: exponentiation_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The exponentiation assignment operator (**=) raises the value of a variable to the power of the right operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Exponentiation assignment (**=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: left_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The left shift assignment operator (<<=) moves the specified amount of bits to the left and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Left shift assignment (<<=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: logical_and_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The logical AND assignment (x &&= y) operator only assigns if x is truthy.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Logical AND assignment (&&=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: logical_nullish_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The logical nullish assignment (x ??= y) operator only assigns if x is nullish (null or undefined).
sec-assignment-operators.title: Logical nullish assignment (??=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: logical_or_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The logical OR assignment (x ||= y) operator only assigns if x is falsy.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Logical OR assignment (||=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: multiplication_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The multiplication assignment operator (*=) multiplies a variable by the value of the right operand and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Multiplication assignment (*=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: remainder_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The remainder assignment operator (%=) divides a variable by the value of the right operand and assigns the remainder to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Remainder assignment (%=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: right_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The right shift assignment operator (>>=) moves the specified amount of bits to the right and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Right shift assignment (>>=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: subtraction_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The subtraction assignment operator (-=) subtracts the value of the right operand from a variable and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Subtraction assignment (-=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: unsigned_right_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The unsigned right shift assignment operator (>>>=) moves the specified amount of bits to the right and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Unsigned right shift assignment (>>>=)

sec-async-function-definitions.name: async_function
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The async function keyword can be used to define async functions inside expressions.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: async function expression

sec-async-function-definitions.name: top_level
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The await operator is used to wait for a Promise and get its fulfillment value. It can only be used inside an async function or a JavaScript module.

nodejs.notes: Not supported in CommonJS modules.
Not supported in CommonJS modules.

sec-async-function-definitions.title: await

sec-async-function-definitions.name: await
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The await operator is used to wait for a Promise and get its fulfillment value. It can only be used inside an async function or a JavaScript module.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: await

sec-async-function-definitions.name: async_function
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: An async function is a function declared with the async keyword, and the await keyword is permitted within it. The async and await keywords enable asynchronous, promise-based behavior to be written in a cleaner style, avoiding the need to explicitly configure promise chains.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: async function

sec-async-generator-function-definitions.name: async_generator_function
sec-async-generator-function-definitions.summary: The async function* keywords can be used to define an asynchronous generator function inside an expression.
sec-async-generator-function-definitions.title: async function* expression

sec-async-generator-function-definitions.name: async_generator_function
sec-async-generator-function-definitions.summary: The async function* declaration defines an async generator function, which returns an AsyncGenerator object.
sec-async-generator-function-definitions.title: async function*

prod-BitwiseANDExpression.name: bitwise_and
prod-BitwiseANDExpression.summary: The bitwise AND operator (&) returns a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of both operands are 1s.
prod-BitwiseANDExpression.title: Bitwise AND (&)

sec-bitwise-not-operator.name: bitwise_not
sec-bitwise-not-operator.summary: The bitwise NOT operator (~) inverts the bits of its operand. Like other bitwise operators, it converts the operand to a 32-bit signed integer
sec-bitwise-not-operator.title: Bitwise NOT (~)

prod-BitwiseORExpression.name: bitwise_or
prod-BitwiseORExpression.summary: The bitwise OR operator (|) returns a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of either or both operands are 1s.
prod-BitwiseORExpression.title: Bitwise OR (|)

prod-BitwiseXORExpression.name: bitwise_xor
prod-BitwiseXORExpression.summary: The bitwise XOR operator (^) returns a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of either but not both operands are 1s.
prod-BitwiseXORExpression.title: Bitwise XOR (^)

sec-comma-operator.name: comma
sec-comma-operator.summary: The comma operator (,) evaluates each of its operands (from left to right) and returns the value of the last operand. This lets you create a compound expression in which multiple expressions are evaluated, with the compound expression's final value being the value of the rightmost of its member expressions. This is commonly used to provide multiple parameters to a for loop.
sec-comma-operator.title: Comma operator (,)

sec-conditional-operator.name: conditional
sec-conditional-operator.summary: The conditional (ternary) operator is the only JavaScript operator that takes three operands: a condition followed by a question mark (?), then an expression to execute if the condition is truthy followed by a colon (:), and finally the expression to execute if the condition is falsy. This operator is frequently used as an alternative to an if...else statement.
sec-conditional-operator.title: Conditional (ternary) operator

sec-postfix-decrement-operator.name: decrement
sec-postfix-decrement-operator.summary: The decrement operator (--) decrements (subtracts one from) its operand and returns the value before or after the decrement, depending on where the operator is placed.
sec-postfix-decrement-operator.title: Decrement (--)

sec-delete-operator.name: delete
sec-delete-operator.summary: The delete operator removes a property from an object. If the property's value is an object and there are no more references to the object, the object held by that property is eventually released automatically.
sec-delete-operator.title: delete operator

sec-destructuring-assignment.name: destructuring
sec-destructuring-assignment.summary: The destructuring assignment syntax is a JavaScript expression that makes it possible to unpack values from arrays, or properties from objects, into distinct variables.

firefox.notes: Firefox provided a non-standard destructuring implementation from Firefox 2 to 40.

sec-destructuring-assignment.title: Destructuring assignment

sec-destructuring-binding-patterns.name: destructuring
sec-destructuring-binding-patterns.summary: The destructuring assignment syntax is a JavaScript expression that makes it possible to unpack values from arrays, or properties from objects, into distinct variables.

firefox.notes: Firefox provided a non-standard destructuring implementation from Firefox 2 to 40.

sec-destructuring-binding-patterns.title: Destructuring assignment

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: division
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The division operator (/) produces the quotient of its operands where the left operand is the dividend and the right operand is the divisor.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Division (/)

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: multiplication
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The multiplication operator (*) produces the product of the operands.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Multiplication (*)

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: remainder
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The remainder operator (%) returns the remainder left over when one operand is divided by a second operand. It always takes the sign of the dividend.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Remainder (%)

sec-equality-operators.name: equality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The equality operator (==) checks whether its two operands are equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the strict equality operator, it attempts to convert and compare operands that are of different types.
sec-equality-operators.title: Equality (==)

sec-equality-operators.name: inequality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The inequality operator (!=) checks whether its two operands are not equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the strict inequality operator, it attempts to convert and compare operands that are of different types.
sec-equality-operators.title: Inequality (!=)

sec-equality-operators.name: strict_equality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The strict equality operator (===) checks whether its two operands are equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the equality operator, the strict equality operator always considers operands of different types to be different.
sec-equality-operators.title: Strict equality (===)

sec-equality-operators.name: strict_inequality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The strict inequality operator (!==) checks whether its two operands are not equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the inequality operator, the strict inequality operator always considers operands of different types to be different.
sec-equality-operators.title: Strict inequality (!==)

sec-exp-operator.name: exponentiation
sec-exp-operator.summary: The exponentiation operator (**) returns the result of raising the first operand to the power of the second operand. It is equivalent to Math.pow(), except it also accepts BigInts as operands.
sec-exp-operator.title: Exponentiation (**)

sec-generator-function-definitions.name: generator_function
sec-generator-function-definitions.summary: The function* keyword can be used to define a generator function inside an expression.
sec-generator-function-definitions.title: function* expression

sec-generator-function-definitions.name: generator_function
sec-generator-function-definitions.summary: The function* declaration (function keyword followed by an asterisk) defines a generator function, which returns a Generator object.
sec-generator-function-definitions.title: function*

sec-relational-operators.name: greater_than
sec-relational-operators.summary: The greater than operator (>) returns true if the left operand is greater than the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Greater than (>)

sec-relational-operators.name: greater_than_or_equal
sec-relational-operators.summary: The greater than or equal operator (>=) returns true if the left operand is greater than or equal to the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Greater than or equal (>=)

sec-relational-operators.name: in
sec-relational-operators.summary: The in operator returns true if the specified property is in the specified object or its prototype chain.
sec-relational-operators.title: in operator

sec-relational-operators.name: instanceof
sec-relational-operators.summary: The instanceof operator tests to see if the prototype property of a constructor appears anywhere in the prototype chain of an object. The return value is a boolean value. Its behavior can be customized with Symbol.hasInstance.
sec-relational-operators.title: instanceof

sec-relational-operators.name: less_than
sec-relational-operators.summary: The less than operator (<) returns true if the left operand is less than the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Less than (<)

sec-relational-operators.name: less_than_or_equal
sec-relational-operators.summary: The less than or equal operator (<=) returns true if the left operand is less than or equal to the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Less than or equal (<=)

sec-grouping-operator.name: grouping
sec-grouping-operator.summary: The grouping operator ( ) controls the precedence of evaluation in expressions.
sec-grouping-operator.title: Grouping operator ( )

sec-import-calls.name: import
sec-import-calls.summary: The import() call, commonly called dynamic import, is a function-like expression that allows loading an ECMAScript module asynchronously and dynamically into a potentially non-module environment.

nodejs.notes: Dynamic import can be used in either CommonJS or ES module files, to import either CommonJS or ES module files. See Node's ECMAScript Modules documentation for more details.
Dynamic import can be used in either CommonJS or ES module files, to import either CommonJS or ES module files. See Node's ECMAScript Modules documentation for more details.

sec-import-calls.title: import

prod-ImportMeta.name: import_meta
prod-ImportMeta.summary: The import.meta object exposes context-specific metadata to a JavaScript module. It contains information about the module, like the module's URL.
prod-ImportMeta.title: import.meta

sec-postfix-increment-operator.name: increment
sec-postfix-increment-operator.summary: The increment operator (++) increments (adds one to) its operand and returns the value before or after the increment, depending on where the operator is placed.
sec-postfix-increment-operator.title: Increment (++)

sec-left-shift-operator.name: left_shift
sec-left-shift-operator.summary: The left shift operator (<<) shifts the first operand the specified number of bits, modulo 32, to the left. Excess bits shifted off to the left are discarded. Zero bits are shifted in from the right.
sec-left-shift-operator.title: Left shift (<<)

prod-LogicalANDExpression.name: logical_and
prod-LogicalANDExpression.summary: The logical AND (&&) operator (logical conjunction) for a set of boolean operands will be true if and only if all the operands are true. Otherwise it will be false.
prod-LogicalANDExpression.title: Logical AND (&&)

sec-logical-not-operator.name: logical_not
sec-logical-not-operator.summary: The logical NOT (!) operator (logical complement, negation) takes truth to falsity and vice versa. It is typically used with boolean (logical) values. When used with non-Boolean values, it returns false if its single operand can be converted to true; otherwise, returns true.
sec-logical-not-operator.title: Logical NOT (!)

prod-LogicalORExpression.name: logical_or
prod-LogicalORExpression.summary: The logical OR (||) operator (logical disjunction) for a set of operands is true if and only if one or more of its operands is true. It is typically used with boolean (logical) values. When it is, it returns a Boolean value. However, the || operator actually returns the value of one of the specified operands, so if this operator is used with non-Boolean values, it will return a non-Boolean value.
prod-LogicalORExpression.title: Logical OR (||)

sec-new-operator.name: new
sec-new-operator.summary: The new operator lets developers create an instance of a user-defined object type or of one of the built-in object types that has a constructor function.
sec-new-operator.title: new operator

sec-built-in-function-objects.name: new_target
sec-built-in-function-objects.summary: The new.target pseudo-property lets you detect whether a function or constructor was called using the new operator. In constructors and functions invoked using the new operator, new.target returns a reference to the constructor or function. In normal function calls, new.target is undefined.
sec-built-in-function-objects.title: new.target

sec-null-value.name: null
sec-null-value.summary: The value null represents the intentional absence of any object value. It is one of JavaScript's primitive values and is treated as falsy for boolean operations.
sec-null-value.title: null

prod-CoalesceExpression.name: nullish_coalescing
prod-CoalesceExpression.summary: The nullish coalescing operator (??) is a logical operator that returns its right-hand side operand when its left-hand side operand is null or undefined, and otherwise returns its left-hand side operand.
prod-CoalesceExpression.title: Nullish coalescing operator (??)

sec-object-initializer.name: object_initializer
sec-object-initializer.summary: Objects can be initialized using new Object(), Object.create(), or using the literal notation (initializer notation). An object initializer is a comma-delimited list of zero or more pairs of property names and associated values of an object, enclosed in curly braces ({}).
sec-object-initializer.title: Object initializer

prod-OptionalExpression.name: optional_chaining
prod-OptionalExpression.summary: The optional chaining operator (?.) accesses an object's property or calls a function. If the object is undefined or null, it returns undefined instead of throwing an error.
prod-OptionalExpression.title: Optional chaining (?.)

sec-property-accessors.name: property_accessors
sec-property-accessors.summary: Property accessors provide access to an object's properties by using the dot notation or the bracket notation.
sec-property-accessors.title: Property accessors

sec-signed-right-shift-operator.name: right_shift
sec-signed-right-shift-operator.summary: The right shift operator (>>) returns the signed number represented by the result of performing a sign-extending shift of the binary representation of the first operand (evaluated as a two's complement bit string) to the right by the number of bits, modulo 32, specified in the second operand. Excess bits shifted off to the right are discarded, and copies of the leftmost bit are shifted in from the left.
sec-signed-right-shift-operator.title: Right shift (>>)

prod-SpreadElement.name: spread_in_arrays
prod-SpreadElement.summary: Spread syntax (...) allows an iterable, such as an array or string, to be expanded in places where zero or more arguments (for function calls) or elements (for array literals) are expected. In an object literal, the spread syntax enumerates the properties of an object and adds the key-value pairs to the object being created.
prod-SpreadElement.title: Spread syntax (...)

sec-subtraction-operator-minus.name: subtraction
sec-subtraction-operator-minus.summary: The subtraction operator (-) subtracts the two operands, producing their difference.
sec-subtraction-operator-minus.title: Subtraction (-)

sec-super-keyword.name: super
sec-super-keyword.summary: The super keyword is used to access properties on an object literal or class's [[Prototype]], or invoke a superclass's constructor.
sec-super-keyword.title: super

sec-this-keyword.name: this
sec-this-keyword.summary: A function's this keyword behaves a little differently in JavaScript compared to other languages. It also has some differences between strict mode and non-strict mode.
sec-this-keyword.title: this

sec-typeof-operator.name: typeof
sec-typeof-operator.summary: The typeof operator returns a string indicating the type of the operand's value.
sec-typeof-operator.title: typeof

sec-unary-minus-operator.name: unary_negation
sec-unary-minus-operator.summary: The unary negation operator (-) precedes its operand and negates it.
sec-unary-minus-operator.title: Unary negation (-)

sec-unary-plus-operator.name: unary_plus
sec-unary-plus-operator.summary: The unary plus operator (+) precedes its operand and evaluates to its operand but attempts to convert it into a number, if it isn't already.
sec-unary-plus-operator.title: Unary plus (+)

sec-unsigned-right-shift-operator.name: unsigned_right_shift
sec-unsigned-right-shift-operator.summary: The unsigned right shift operator (>>>) (zero-fill right shift) evaluates the left-hand operand as an unsigned number, and shifts the binary representation of that number by the number of bits, modulo 32, specified by the right-hand operand. Excess bits shifted off to the right are discarded, and zero bits are shifted in from the left. The sign bit becomes 0, so the result is always non-negative. Unlike the other bitwise operators, zero-fill right shift returns an unsigned 32-bit integer.
sec-unsigned-right-shift-operator.title: Unsigned right shift (>>>)

sec-void-operator.name: void
sec-void-operator.summary: The void operator evaluates the given expression and then returns undefined.
sec-void-operator.title: void operator

prod-YieldExpression.name: yield
prod-YieldExpression.summary: The yield keyword is used to pause and resume a generator function.

notes: Starting with Firefox 33, the parsing of the yield expression has been updated to conform with the ES2015 specification.
Starting with Firefox 29, an IteratorResult object returned for completed generator function.

prod-YieldExpression.title: yield

sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.name: yield_star
sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.summary: The yield* expression is used to delegate to another generator or iterable object.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 33, the parsing of the yield expression has been updated to conform with the ES2015 specification.

sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.title: yield*

sec-block.name: block
sec-block.summary: A block statement is used to group zero or more statements. The block is delimited by a pair of braces ("curly brackets") and contains a list of zero or more statements and declarations.
sec-block.title: block

sec-break-statement.name: break
sec-break-statement.summary: The break statement terminates the current loop, switch, or label statement and transfers program control to the statement following the terminated statement.
sec-break-statement.title: break

sec-let-and-const-declarations.name: const
sec-let-and-const-declarations.summary: Constants are block-scoped, much like variables declared using the let keyword. The value of a constant can't be changed through reassignment (i.e. by using the assignment operator), and it can't be redeclared (i.e. through a variable declaration). However, if a constant is an object or array its properties or items can be updated or removed.

notes: Before Firefox 13, const is implemented, but re-assignment is not failing.
Before Firefox 46, a TypeError was thrown on redeclaration instead of a SyntaxError.

sec-let-and-const-declarations.title: const

sec-let-and-const-declarations.name: let
sec-let-and-const-declarations.summary: The let declaration declares a block-scoped local variable, optionally initializing it to a value.

notes: Before Firefox 44, let is only available to code blocks in HTML wrapped in a <script type="application/javascript;version=1.7"> block (or higher version) and has different semantics (e.g. no temporal dead zone).
Before Firefox 46, a TypeError is thrown on redeclaration instead of a SyntaxError.
Firefox 54 adds support of let in workers.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer, let within a for loop initializer does not create a separate variable for each loop iteration as defined by ES2015. Instead, it behaves as though the loop were wrapped in a scoping block with the let immediately before the loop.

sec-let-and-const-declarations.title: let

sec-continue-statement.name: continue
sec-continue-statement.summary: The continue statement terminates execution of the statements in the current iteration of the current or labeled loop, and continues execution of the loop with the next iteration.
sec-continue-statement.title: continue

sec-debugger-statement.name: debugger
sec-debugger-statement.summary: The debugger statement invokes any available debugging functionality, such as setting a breakpoint. If no debugging functionality is available, this statement has no effect.
sec-debugger-statement.title: debugger

sec-do-while-statement.name: do_while
sec-do-while-statement.summary: The do...while statement creates a loop that executes a specified statement until the test condition evaluates to false. The condition is evaluated after executing the statement, resulting in the specified statement executing at least once.
sec-do-while-statement.title: do...while

sec-empty-statement.name: empty
sec-empty-statement.summary: An empty statement is used to provide no statement, although the JavaScript syntax would expect one.
sec-empty-statement.title: empty

sec-for-statement.name: for
sec-for-statement.summary: The for statement creates a loop that consists of three optional expressions, enclosed in parentheses and separated by semicolons, followed by a statement (usually a block statement) to be executed in the loop.
sec-for-statement.title: for

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_await_of
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for await...of statement creates a loop iterating over async iterable objects as well as sync iterables. This statement can only be used in contexts where await can be used, which includes inside an async function body and in a module.
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for await...of

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_in
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for...in statement iterates over all enumerable string properties of an object (ignoring properties keyed by symbols), including inherited enumerable properties.
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for...in

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_of
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for...of statement executes a loop that operates on a sequence of values sourced from an iterable object. Iterable objects include instances of built-ins such as Array, String, TypedArray, Map, Set, NodeList (and other DOM collections), as well as the arguments object, generators produced by generator functions, and user-defined iterables.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 51, using the for...of loop construct with the const keyword threw a SyntaxError ("missing = in const declaration").

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for...of

sec-if-statement.name: if_else
sec-if-statement.summary: The if statement executes a statement if a specified condition is truthy. If the condition is falsy, another statement in the optional else clause will be executed.
sec-if-statement.title: if...else

sec-imports.name: import
sec-imports.summary: The static import declaration is used to import read-only live bindings which are exported by another module. The imported bindings are called live bindings because they are updated by the module that exported the binding, but cannot be modified by the importing module.

sec-imports.title: import

sec-labelled-statements.name: label
sec-labelled-statements.summary: The labeled statement can be used with break or continue statements. It is prefixing a statement with an identifier which you can refer to.
sec-labelled-statements.title: label

sec-return-statement.name: return
sec-return-statement.summary: The return statement ends function execution and specifies a value to be returned to the function caller.
sec-return-statement.title: return

sec-switch-statement.name: switch
sec-switch-statement.summary: The switch statement evaluates an expression, matching the expression's value against a series of case clauses, and executes statements after the first case clause with a matching value, until a break statement is encountered. The default clause of a switch statement will be jumped to if no case matches the expression's value.
sec-switch-statement.title: switch

sec-throw-statement.name: throw
sec-throw-statement.summary: The throw statement throws a user-defined exception. Execution of the current function will stop (the statements after throw won't be executed), and control will be passed to the first catch block in the call stack. If no catch block exists among caller functions, the program will terminate.
sec-throw-statement.title: throw

sec-try-statement.name: try_catch
sec-try-statement.summary: The try...catch statement is comprised of a try block and either a catch block, a finally block, or both. The code in the try block is executed first, and if it throws an exception, the code in the catch block will be executed. The code in the finally block will always be executed before control flow exits the entire construct.
sec-try-statement.title: try...catch

sec-variable-statement.name: var
sec-variable-statement.summary: The var statement declares a function-scoped or globally-scoped variable, optionally initializing it to a value.
sec-variable-statement.title: var

sec-while-statement.name: while
sec-while-statement.summary: The while statement creates a loop that executes a specified statement as long as the test condition evaluates to true. The condition is evaluated before executing the statement.
sec-while-statement.title: while
